            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Linked Lists — What & Why

            ## What is a Linked List?

            A **linked list** is a linear data structure where:
            - Elements (**nodes**) are stored **non-contiguously**
            - Each node contains:
              - **Data**
              - A **reference (pointer)** to the next node

            ### Why use linked lists?
            - Efficient **insertions and deletions**
            - No need for contiguous memory
            - Dynamic size

            ### Key trade-off
            No direct access by index (unlike arrays)

            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Linked Lists — Node Structure

            ## Anatomy of a Node

            Each node has two parts:
            - **Value**
            - **Next pointer**

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              N1["Data | Next"] --> N2["Data | Next"];
              N2 --> N3["Data | Next"];
              N3 --> Null["NULL"];
            /mermaid

            ### Important terms
            - **Head** → first node
            - **Tail** → last node
            - **NULL** → end of the list

            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Singly Linked Lists

            ## Singly Linked List

            Each node points **only to the next node**

            mermaid
            graph LR;
              A --> B --> C --> D --> Null;
            /mermaid

            ### Characteristics
            - Traversal in **one direction**
            - Lower memory usage
            - Simple implementation

            ### Operations
            - Insert: O(1) (if position known)
            - Delete: O(1) (if node known)
            - Search: O(n)

            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Doubly Linked Lists

            ## Doubly Linked List

            Each node points to:
            - **Next node**
            - **Previous node**

            mermaid
            graph LR
              Null1["NULL"] <--- A <---> B <---> C ---> Null2["NULL"]
            /mermaid

            ### Advantages
            - Traverse **forward and backward**
            - Easier deletion of a given node

            ### Disadvantages
            - Extra memory for previous pointer
            - Slightly more complex logic

            </script>

          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Circular Linked Lists

            ## Circular Linked Lists

            The last node points back to the **head**

            ### Singly Circular
            mermaid
            graph LR;
              A --> B --> C --> A;
            /mermaid

            ### Doubly Circular
            mermaid
            graph LR;
              A <--> B <--> C <--> A;
            /mermaid

            ### Use cases
            - Round-robin scheduling
            - Infinite loops / cyclic data
            - Playlists

            </script>

          </div>
        </div>
        
